			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Yes, it would be helpful to know what kind of audio equipment you have now.
<br />

<br />
I'm thinking dual-cpu is a must (zero latency, no waiting, better number crunching, infinitely superior multitasking). Also I'd go for a RAID-1 or RAID-5 configuration for your data. You don't want to lose your mixing work to a glitch in hardware. Oh, and you'll want the ability to stream your recordings to two differnet locations so that you always have a backup of the original somewhere. There are plenty of times when the audio software can bork the heck out of your original recordings, and having that backup copy automatically saved somewhere else during recording sessions can save you the trouble of getting the band back in the studio again.
<br />

<br />
I'm a bit of a noob when it comes to audio equipment, but the computer I can do np. I'm sure there are some studio type hackers reading the board, hopefully they'll chime in to fill in the gaps. Just so damn busy today at work (for a change) that I'm having trouble finding time to visit the boards...<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
