			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I'm sorry, but the only RAID level that offers a performance boost is RAID 0. That's because access times are divided among the array without the burden of parity. If you don't believe me, check out this link for an IDE RAID summary:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www6.tomshardware.com/storage/20020813/ide-raid-03.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://www6.tomshardware.com/storage/20020813/ide-raid-03.html</a>
<br />

<br />
~edit - Yes, I know IDE != SATA, but the overhead of parity/mirroring still applies since the RAID controller has to access more than one drive per read/write request.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
