	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><span class="name"><a name="51699"></a><b>EvilNight</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Agent of the System<br />
		<br /><img class="avatar" src="http://www.eqluclin.com/forum/images/avatars/bunbun.gif" alt="" /><br />
		<br />Joined: 19 Jul 2003<br />Posts: 1389</span></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=51699&amp;sid=fe872ddcba656edbafb507c096222d28#51699"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Wed Feb 25, 2004 4:45 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Rav, build me a auido production PC!</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=51699&amp;sid=fe872ddcba656edbafb507c096222d28"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I'm sorry, but the only RAID level that offers a performance boost is RAID 0. <span style="font-weight: bold">That's because access times are divided among the array without the burden of parity. </span> If you don't believe me, check out this link for an IDE RAID summary: </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You're still under the assumption that parity creates a burden. It does not. Any decent raid controller has parity algorithms built in to the card's hardware, completely negating the performance hit. 3Ware cards, for example, suffer no performance hit whatsoever from it, and perform the exact same speed in RAID0 and RAID5. I build about one of these a week, and I've benched them many times.
<br />

<br />
In addition, the overhead generated on systems without the benefit of this kind of parity-boosting algorithm are still faster than single disk systems. When you stripe three disks, you gain three times the disk i/o bandwidth. If you lose one of those disks to parity, you are still operating at double the i/o bandwidth of a single disk.
<br />

<br />
By and large, the idea that using any form of RAID leads to a performance problem is a complete myth.
<br />

<br />
By the way, the benchmarks at this link are wholly wrong:
<br />
<a href="http://tech-report.com/reviews/2002q4/ideraid/index.x?pg=27" target="_blank">http://tech-report.com/reviews/2002q4/ideraid/index.x?pg=27</a>
<br />

<br />
I get an average of eighty (80) megabytes a second of throughput to my 3ware escalade raids (typically 3 to 6 disk configuration, raid5). The benchmarks he is posting list a whopping 3 megabytes per second. That's ridiculous. Someone should have helped that guy set up his systems properly for testing...
<br />

<br />
Tom's article is on track, although it is hopelessly out of date. A year ago, IDE raid controllers were just barely catching up to their SCSI brethren. Today they've rather outstripped them, especially with ATA133 and SATA. A SATA raid built on Western Digital Raptor drives is one badass performer. I've benched data bursts over 200MB/sec in those situations.
<br />

<br />
The only thing that does suffer is the access time. Access times of a single disk will be slightly faster than similar raided disks, because the data has to go through more hardware layers to find its way to the computer. Typically you are talking about one or two miliseconds, though, so it's never going to matter for someone unless they are trying to host slashdot or CNN.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Comparing apples to apples, a single SATA drive will outperform a RAID 1 SATA. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No, the RAID1 mirror will outperform the single drive, and here's why: Writes will go at the exact same speed, but read speeds will increase, even double under the right conditions. You can read your data from two separate locations, and any RAID controller worth a dime will stripe the data reads so the throughput increases. Heck even Windows 2000 <span style="font-style: italic">software</span> raid gets this performance increase. So does Linux's software raid. The only thing that will suffer is the access time, and it'll be negligible.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
